# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gate-level-simulation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] A **discrete-event simulation** (**DES**) models the operation of a system as a (discrete) sequence of events in time.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Each event occurs at a particular instant in time and marks a change of state in the system.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Between consecutive events, no change in the system is assumed to occur; thus the simulation time can directly jump to the occurrence time of the next event, which is called **next-event time progression**.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] In addition to next-event time progression, there is also an alternative approach, called **incremental time progression**, where time is broken up into small time slices and the system state is updated according to the set of events/activities happening in the time slice.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Because not every time slice has to be simulated, a next-event time simulation can typically run faster than a corresponding incremental time simulation.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Both forms of DES contrast with continuous simulation in which the system state is changed continuously over time on the basis of a set of differential equations defining the rates of change for state variables.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] In the past, these three types of simulation have also been referred to, respectively, as: event scheduling simulation, activity scanning simulation, and process interaction simulation.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] It can also be noted that there are similarities between the implementation of the event queue in event scheduling, and the scheduling queue used in operating systems.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] A common exercise in learning how to build discrete-event simulations is to model a queueing system, such as customers arriving at a bank teller to be served by a clerk.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] In this example, the system objects are ***customer*** and ***teller***, while the system events are ***customer-arrival***, ***service-start*** and ***service-end***.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] When a *service-start* event occurs, the state variable *teller-status* is set to "busy" and a *service-end* follow-up event is scheduled with a delay (obtained from sampling a *service-time* random variable).
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] When a *service-end* event occurs, the state variable *queue-length* is decremented by 1 (representing the customer's departure).
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] If the state variable *queue-length* is still greater than zero, a *Service-Start* follow-up event is scheduled to happen without any delay.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Otherwise, the state variable *teller-status* is set to "available".
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The random variables that need to be characterized to model this system stochastically are the *interarrival-time* for recurrent *customer-arrival* events and the *service-time* for the delays of *service-end* events.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] A system state is a set of variables that captures the salient properties of the system to be studied.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The state trajectory over time S(t) can be mathematically represented by a step function whose value can change whenever an event occurs.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The simulation must keep track of the current simulation time, in whatever measurement units are suitable for the system being modeled.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] In discrete-event simulations, as opposed to continuous simulations, time 'hops' because events are instantaneous – the clock skips to the next event start time as the simulation proceeds.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The simulation maintains at least one list of simulation events.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] This is sometimes called the *pending event set* because it lists events that are pending as a result of previously simulated event but have yet to be simulated themselves.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] An event is described by the time at which it occurs and a type, indicating the code that will be used to simulate that event.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] It is common for the event code to be parametrized, in which case, the event description also contains parameters to the event code.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The event list is also referred to as the *future event list* (FEL) or *future event set* (FES).
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] When events are instantaneous, activities that extend over time are modeled as sequences of events.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Some simulation frameworks allow the time of an event to be specified as an interval, giving the start time and the end time of each event.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Single-threaded simulation engines based on instantaneous events have just one current event.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] In contrast, multi-threaded simulation engines and simulation engines supporting an interval-based event model may have multiple current events.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] In both cases, there are significant problems with synchronization between current events.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The pending event set is typically organized as a priority queue, sorted by event time.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] That is, regardless of the order in which events are added to the event set, they are removed in strictly chronological order.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Various priority queue implementations have been studied in the context of discrete event simulation; alternatives studied have included splay trees, skip lists, calendar queues, and ladder queues.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] On massively-parallel machines, such as multi-core or many-core CPUs, the pending event set can be implemented by relying on non-blocking algorithms, in order to reduce the cost of synchronization among the concurrent threads.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Typically, events are scheduled dynamically as the simulation proceeds.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] For example, in the bank example noted above, the event CUSTOMER-ARRIVAL at time t would, if the CUSTOMER_QUEUE was empty and TELLER was idle, include the creation of the subsequent event CUSTOMER-DEPARTURE to occur at time t+s, where s is a number generated from the SERVICE-TIME distribution.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The simulation needs to generate random variables of various kinds, depending on the system model.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] This is accomplished by one or more Pseudorandom number generators.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The use of pseudo-random numbers as opposed to true random numbers is a benefit should a simulation need a rerun with exactly the same behavior.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] One of the problems with the random number distributions used in discrete-event simulation is that the steady-state distributions of event times may not be known in advance.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] As a result, the initial set of events placed into the pending event set will not have arrival times representative of the steady-state distribution.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] This problem is typically solved by bootstrapping the simulation model.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Only a limited effort is made to assign realistic times to the initial set of pending events.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] These events, however, schedule additional events, and with time, the distribution of event times approaches its steady state.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] This is called *bootstrapping* the simulation model.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] In gathering statistics from the running model, it is important to either disregard events that occur before the steady state is reached or to run the simulation for long enough that the bootstrapping behavior is overwhelmed by steady-state behavior.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] (This use of the term *bootstrapping* can be contrasted with its use in both statistics and computing).
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The simulation typically keeps track of the system's statistics, which quantify the aspects of interest.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] In the bank example, it is of interest to track the mean waiting times.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] In a simulation model, performance metrics are not analytically derived from probability distributions, but rather as averages over replications, that is different runs of the model.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Confidence intervals are usually constructed to help assess the quality of the output.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Because events are bootstrapped, theoretically a discrete-event simulation could run forever.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] So the simulation designer must decide when the simulation will end.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Typical choices are "at time t" or "after processing n number of events" or, more generally, "when statistical measure X reaches the value x".
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Pidd (1998) has proposed the three-phased approach to discrete event simulation.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] In this approach, the first phase is to jump to the next chronological event.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The second phase is to execute all events that unconditionally occur at that time (these are called B-events).
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The third phase is to execute all events that conditionally occur at that time (these are called C-events).
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The three phase approach is a refinement of the event-based approach in which simultaneous events are ordered so as to make the most efficient use of computer resources.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The three-phase approach is used by a number of commercial simulation software packages, but from the user's point of view, the specifics of the underlying simulation method are generally hidden.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Simulation approaches are particularly well equipped to help users diagnose issues in complex environments.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The theory of constraints illustrates the importance of understanding bottlenecks in a system.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Identifying and removing bottlenecks allows improving processes and the overall system.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] For instance, in manufacturing enterprises bottlenecks may be created by excess inventory, overproduction, variability in processes and variability in routing or sequencing.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] By accurately documenting the system with the help of a simulation model it is possible to gain a bird’s eye view of the entire system.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] A working model of a system allows management to understand performance drivers.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] A simulation can be built to include any number of performance indicators such as worker utilization, on-time delivery rate, scrap rate, cash cycles, and so on.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] An operating theater is generally shared between several surgical disciplines.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Through better understanding the nature of these procedures it may be possible to increase the patient throughput.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Example: If a heart surgery takes on average four hours, changing an operating room schedule from eight available hours to nine will not increase patient throughput.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] On the other hand, if a hernia procedure takes on average twenty minutes providing an extra hour may also not yield any increased throughput if the capacity and average time spent in the recovery room is not considered.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Many systems improvement ideas are built on sound principles, proven methodologies (Lean, Six Sigma, TQM, etc.) yet fail to improve the overall system.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] A simulation model allows the user to understand and test a performance improvement idea in the context of the overall system.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Simulation modeling is commonly used to model potential investments.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Through modeling investments decision-makers can make informed decisions and evaluate potential alternatives.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Discrete event simulation is used in computer network to simulate new protocols, different system architectures (distributed, hierarchical, centralised, P2P) before actual deployment.
[src:gate-level-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] It is possible to define different evaluation metrics, such as service time, bandwidth, dropped packets, resource consumption, and so on.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] Logic simulation may be used as part of the verification process in designing hardware.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] Simulations have the advantage of providing a familiar look and feel to the user in that it is constructed from the same language and symbols used in design.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] By allowing the user to interact directly with the design, simulation is a natural way for the designer to get feedback on their design.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] The level of effort required to debug and then verify the design is proportional to the maturity of the design.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] That is, early in the design's life, bugs and incorrect behavior are usually found quickly.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] As the design matures, the simulation will require more time and resources to run, and errors will take progressively longer to be found.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] This is particularly problematic when simulating components for modern-day systems; every component that changes state in a single clock cycle on the simulation will require several clock cycles to simulate.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] A straightforward approach to this issue may be to emulate the circuit on a field-programmable gate array instead.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] Formal verification can also be explored as an alternative to simulation, although a formal proof is not always possible or convenient.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] A prospective way to accelerate logic simulation is using distributed and parallel computations.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] To help gauge the thoroughness of a simulation, tools exist for assessing code coverage, functional coverage, finite state machine (FSM) coverage, and many other metrics.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] Event simulation allows the design to contain simple timing information – the delay needed for a signal to travel from one place to another.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] During simulation, signal changes are tracked in the form of events.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] A change at a certain time triggers an event after a certain delay.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] Events are sorted by the time when they will occur, and when all events for a particular time have been handled, the simulated time is advanced to the time of the next scheduled event.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] How fast an event simulation runs depends on the number of events to be processed (the amount of activity in the model).
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] While event simulation can provide some feedback regarding signal timing, it is not a replacement for static timing analysis.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] In cycle simulation, it is not possible to specify delays.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] A cycle-accurate model is used, and every gate is evaluated in every cycle.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] Cycle simulation therefore runs at a constant speed, regardless of activity in the model.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] Optimized implementations may take advantage of low model activity to speed up simulation by skipping evaluation of gates whose inputs didn't change.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] In comparison to event simulation, cycle simulation tends to be faster, to scale better, and to be better suited for hardware acceleration / emulation.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] However, chip design trends point to event simulation gaining relative performance due to activity factor reduction in the circuit (due to techniques such as clock gating and power gating, which are becoming much more commonly used in an effort to reduce power dissipation).
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] In these cases, since event simulation only simulates necessary events, performance may no longer be a disadvantage over cycle simulation.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] Event simulation also has the advantage of greater flexibility, handling design features difficult to handle with cycle simulation, such as asynchronous logic and incommensurate clocks.
[src:gate-level-simulation/logic-simulation] Due to these considerations, almost all commercial logic simulators have an event based capability, even if they primarily rely on cycle based techniques.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] In electronic design, a **netlist** is a description of the connectivity of an electronic circuit.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] In its simplest form, a netlist consists of a list of the electronic components in a circuit and a list of the nodes they are connected to.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] A network (net) is a collection of two or more interconnected components.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] The structure, complexity and representation of netlists can vary considerably, but the fundamental purpose of every netlist is to convey connectivity information.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Netlists usually provide nothing more than instances, nodes, and perhaps some attributes of the components involved.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] If they express much more than this, they are usually considered to be a hardware description language such as Verilog or VHDL, or one of several languages specifically designed for input to simulators or hardware compilers (such as SPICE analog simulation netlists).
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Most netlists either contain or refer to descriptions of the parts or devices used.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Each time a part is used in a netlist, this is called an "instance".
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] These descriptions will usually list the connections that are made to that kind of device, and some basic properties of that device.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] These connection points are called "terminals" or "pins", among several other names.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] An "instance" could be anything from a MOSFET transistor or a bipolar junction transistor, to a resistor, a capacitor, or an integrated circuit chip.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] In the case of a vacuum cleaner, these terminals would be the three metal prongs in the plug.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Each terminal has a name, and in continuing the vacuum cleaner example, they might be "Neutral", "Live" and "Ground".
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Usually, each instance will have a unique name, so that if you have two instances of vacuum cleaners, one might be "vac1" and the other "vac2".
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Besides their names, they might otherwise be identical.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Networks (nets) are the "wires" that connect things together in the circuit.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] There may or may not be any special attributes associated with the nets in a design, depending on the particular language the netlist is written in, and that language's features.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Instance based netlists usually provide a list of the instances used in a design.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Along with each instance, either an ordered list of net names is provided, or a list of pairs provided, of an instance port name, along with the net name to which that port is connected.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] In this kind of description, the list of nets can be gathered from the connection lists, and there is no place to associate particular attributes with the nets themselves.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] SPICE is an example of instance-based netlists.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Net-based netlists usually describe all the instances and their attributes, then describe each net, and say which port they are connected on each instance.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] This allows for attributes to be associated with nets.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] EDIF is probably the most famous of the net-based netlists.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] In large designs, it is a common practice to split the design into pieces, each piece becoming a "definition" which can be used as instances in the design.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] In the vacuum cleaner analogy, one might have a vacuum cleaner definition with its ports, but now this definition would also include a full description of the machine's internal components and how they connect (motors, switches, etc.), like a wiring diagram does.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] A definition which includes no instances is called a "primitive" (or a "leaf", or other names); whereas a definition which includes instances is "hierarchical".
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] A "folded" hierarchy allows a single definition to be represented several times by instances.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] An "unfolded" hierarchy does not allow a definition to be used more than once in the hierarchy.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Folded hierarchies can be extremely compact.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] A small netlist of just a few instances can describe designs with a very large number of instances.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] For example, suppose definition A is a simple primitive, like a memory cell.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Then suppose definition B contains 32 instances of A; C contains 32 instances of B; D contains 32 instances of C; and E contains 32 instances of D.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] The design now contains 5 definitions (A through E) and 128 instances.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Yet, E describes a circuit that contains over a million memory cells.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] In a "flat" design, only primitives are instanced.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Hierarchical designs can be recursively "exploded" ("flattened") by creating a new copy (with a new name) of each definition each time it is used.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] If the design is highly folded, expanding it like this will result in a much larger netlist database, but preserves the hierarchy dependencies.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Given a hierarchical netlist, the list of instance names in a path from the root definition to a primitive instance specifies the single unique path to that primitive.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] The paths to every primitive, taken together, comprise a large but flat netlist that is exactly equivalent to the compact hierarchical version.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Backannotation is data that could be added to a hierarchical netlist.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Usually they are kept separate from the netlist, because several such alternate sets of data could be applied to a single netlist.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] These data may have been extracted from a physical design, and might provide extra information for more accurate simulations.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Usually the data are composed of a hierarchical path and a piece of data for that primitive or finding the values of RC delay due to interconnection.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Another concept often used in netlists is that of inheritance.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Suppose a definition of a capacitor has an associated attribute called "Capacitance", corresponding to the physical property of the same name, with a default value of "100 pF" (100 picofarads).
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] Each instance of this capacitor might also have such an attribute, only with a different value of capacitance.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] And other instances might not associate any capacitance at all.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] In the case where no capacitance is specified for an instance, the instance will "inherit" the 100 pF value from its definition.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] A value specified will "override" the value on the definition.
[src:gate-level-simulation/netlist] If a great number of attributes end up being the same as on the definition, a great amount of information can be "inherited", and not have to be redundantly specified in the netlist, saving space, and making the design easier to read by both machines and people.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] In digital circuit design, **register-transfer level** (**RTL**) is a design abstraction which models a synchronous digital circuit in terms of the flow of digital signals (data) between hardware registers, and the logical operations performed on those signals.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] Register-transfer-level abstraction is used in hardware description languages (HDLs) like Verilog and VHDL to create high-level representations of a circuit, from which lower-level representations and ultimately actual wiring can be derived.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] Design at the RTL level is typical practice in modern digital design.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] Unlike in software compiler design, where the register-transfer level is an intermediate representation and at the lowest level, the RTL level is the usual input that circuit designers operate on.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] In circuit synthesis, an intermediate language between the input register transfer level representation and the target netlist is sometimes used.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] Unlike in netlist, constructs such as cells, functions, and multi-bit registers are available.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] Transaction-level modeling is a higher level of electronic system design.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] A synchronous circuit consists of two kinds of elements: registers (sequential logic) and combinational logic.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] Registers (usually implemented as D flip-flops) synchronize the circuit's operation to the edges of the clock signal, and are the only elements in the circuit that have memory properties.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] Combinational logic performs all the logical functions in the circuit and it typically consists of logic gates.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] For example, a very simple synchronous circuit is shown in the figure.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] The inverter is connected from the output, Q, of a register to the register's input, D, to create a circuit that changes its state on each rising edge of the clock, clk.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] In this circuit, the combinational logic consists of the inverter.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] When designing digital integrated circuits with a hardware description language (HDL), the designs are usually engineered at a higher level of abstraction than transistor level (logic families) or logic gate level.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] In HDLs the designer declares the registers (which roughly correspond to variables in computer programming languages), and describes the combinational logic by using constructs that are familiar from programming languages such as if-then-else and arithmetic operations.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] This level is called *register-transfer level*.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] The term refers to the fact that RTL focuses on describing the flow of signals between registers.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] Using an EDA tool for synthesis, this description can usually be directly translated to an equivalent hardware implementation file for an ASIC or an FPGA.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] The synthesis tool also performs logic optimization.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] At the register-transfer level, some types of circuits can be recognized.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] If there is a cyclic path of logic from a register's output to its input (or from a set of registers outputs to its inputs), the circuit is called a state machine or can be said to be sequential logic.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] If there are logic paths from a register to another without a cycle, it is called a pipeline.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] RTL is used in the logic design phase of the integrated circuit design cycle.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] An RTL description is usually converted to a gate-level description of the circuit by a logic synthesis tool.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] The synthesis results are then used by placement and routing tools to create a physical layout.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] Logic simulation tools may use a design's RTL description to verify its correctness.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] The most accurate power analysis tools are available for the circuit level but unfortunately, even with switch- rather than device-level modelling, tools at the circuit level have disadvantages like they are either too slow or require too much memory thus inhibiting large chip handling.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] The majority of these are simulators like SPICE and have been used by the designers for many years as performance analysis tools.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] Due to these disadvantages, gate-level power estimation tools have begun to gain some acceptance where faster, probabilistic techniques have begun to gain a foothold.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] But it also has its trade off as speedup is achieved on the cost of accuracy, especially in the presence of correlated signals.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] Over the years it has been realized that biggest wins in low power design cannot come from circuit- and gate-level optimizations whereas architecture, system, and algorithm optimizations tend to have the largest impact on power consumption.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] Therefore, there has been a shift in the incline of the tool developers towards high-level analysis and optimization tools for power.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] This in no way implies that lower level tools are unimportant.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] Instead, each layer of tools provides a foundation upon which the next level can be built.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] The abstractions of the estimation techniques at a lower level can be used on a higher level with slight modifications.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] It is a technique based on the concept of gate equivalents.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] The complexity of a chip architecture can be described approximately in terms of gate equivalents where gate equivalent count specifies the average number of reference gates that are required to implement the particular function.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] The total power required for the particular function is estimated by multiplying the approximated number of gate equivalents with the average power consumed per gate.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] Assign a complexity in terms of gate equivalents.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] The number of GE’s for each unit type are either taken directly as an input from the user or are fed from a library.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] is the assumed average dissipated energy by a gate equivalent, when active.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] , denotes the average percentage of gates switching per clock cycle and is allowed to vary from function to function.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] , is a combination of fan-out loading as well as wiring.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] An estimate of the average wire length can be used to calculate the wiring capacitance.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] The percentage of gates switching per clock cycle denoted by activity factors are assumed to be fixed regardless of the input patterns.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] Typical gate switching energy is characterized by completely random uniform white noise (UWN) distribution of the input data.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] This implies that the power estimation is same regardless of the circuit being idle or at maximum load as this UWN model ignores how different input distributions affect the power consumption of gates and modules.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] denotes the loading due to a single cell hanging off the bit line.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] The chosen activity factor gives the correct total power, but the breakdown of power into logic, clock, memory, etc. is less accurate.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] Therefore this tool is not much different or improved in comparison with CES.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] Where Ki is PFA proportionality constant that characterizes the ith functional element $G_{i}$ is the measure of hardware complexity, and $f_{i}$ denotes the activation frequency.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] Gi denoting the hardware complexity of the multiplier is related to the square of the input word length i.e.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] The activation frequency is the rate at which multiplies are performed by the algorithm denoted by $f_{mult}$ and the PFA constant, $K_{mult}$ , is extracted empirically from past multiplier designs and shown to be about 15 fW/bit2-Hz for a 1.2 μm technology at 5V.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] The estimation error (relative to switch-level simulation) for a 16x16 multiplier is experimented and it is observed that when the dynamic range of the inputs does not fully occupy the word length of the multiplier, the UWN model becomes extremely inaccurate.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] Granted, good designers attempt to maximize word length utilization.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] Still, errors in the range of 50-100% are not uncommon.
[src:gate-level-simulation/register-transfer-level] The figure clearly suggests a flaw in the UWN model.
[src:gate-level-simulation/standard-delay-format] It was originally developed as an OVI standard, and later modified into the IEEE format.
[src:gate-level-simulation/standard-delay-format] Technically only the SDF version 4.0 onwards are IEEE formats.
[src:gate-level-simulation/standard-delay-format] It is an ASCII format that is represented in a tool and language independent way and includes path delays, timing constraint values, interconnect delays and high level technology parameters.
[src:gate-level-simulation/standard-delay-format] It has usually two sections: one for interconnect delays and the other for cell delays.
[src:gate-level-simulation/standard-delay-format] SDF format can be used for back-annotation as well as forward-annotation.
